Chopping Down the Syntax Tree 
(version 2)


If Noam Chomsky’s Visiting Martian would travel back to earth to catch up with the latest developments in linguistics, they would be intrigued by a new species of language researchers: construction grammarians. Construction grammarians come in all shapes and sizes, but they all agree on the idea that all linguistic information can be represented by a single data structure: constructions. This idea revolutionizes how we conceive of the human language capacity: no more separation between words and syntax, no more distinction between rules and exceptions, and no more need to split up language into different modules. But what exactly is a construction and what can it do?


Construction grammarians tend to avoid to use tree diagrams for analyzing the structure of sentences that other linguists love so much. 




